When do NFL lineups get confirmed?

NFL lineups are officially confirmed on game day when the league releases the inactives list 90 minutes before kickoff of each game. That's when you know for certain if a questionable player (like someone listed with an injury) is going to play. While RotoWire will show players as "probable, questionable, or doubtful" throughout the week, the true confirmation only arrives with the official report.

When to expect lineup changes?

Lineup changes can pop up in practice, outside of the official inactives list. Wednesday–Friday practice reports drive early lineup changes, using Sunday games as a reference. A DNP (did not practice) on a Friday is usually a red flag. Teams often downgrade players Saturday evening after final walkthroughs if they don't respond well. Game-day warmups are an indicator, too; plus, late lineup scratches can still happen even if someone was not on the injury report.

Where to find the latest information?

The best places to track last-minute lineup news and inactives for NFL games, especially useful for fantasy football, include official sources, like the NFL Communications site, team sites and team social media accounts. Plus, you will always be in the know with the RotoWire NFL starting lineups tool. This custom feature allows you to add lineup alerts for the teams and games that matter to you.
